task_1.query_used: Search LinkedIn for professional profile and work history of Ali Khaledi Nasab
task_1.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and AI scientist currently working at Amazon Rufus. Originally from Iran, he moved to the United States in 2014 to pursue his Ph.D. After completing his doctoral studies, he joined Stanford University's Department of Neurosurgery as a research scientist. Subsequently, he worked at CODA Biotherapeutics, a gene therapy startup focused on developing treatments for epilepsy. In 2022, he joined Amazon as a research scientist in the AWS network capacity team. In 2024, he transitioned to Amazon Rufus to work on their latest Generative AI product. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

Throughout his career, Dr. Khaledi Nasab has been involved in various research projects, including studying the dynamics of excitable tree networks in sensory neurons and developing stimulation methods for neurological disorders. He has also contributed to the Encyclopedia of Child and Adolescent Health, which received the 2024 PROSE Award for "significant contributions" in Clinical Medicine. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

In addition to his professional work, Dr. Khaledi Nasab has been active in addressing challenges faced by international students in the U.S., sharing his experiences and advocating for support. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

task_2.query_used: Check online news archives and media databases for mentions of Ali Khaledi Nasab
task_2.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist whose research focuses on the dynamics of excitable tree networks, particularly in sensory neurons. He has presented his work at various conferences, including the American Physical Society's annual meeting in 2019, where he discussed the "Dynamics of excitable tree networks: Application to sensory neurons." ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2019/05/khaledi-nasab-receives-aps-travel-award-to-attend-conference/?utm_source=openai))

In 2017, Nasab gave a colloquium talk at the College of Wooster titled "Emergent stochastic oscillations and signal detection in tree networks of excitable elements," exploring the stochastic dynamics of tree networks in sensory neurons. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2017/10/khaledi-nasab-gives-colloquium-talk-college-wooster/?utm_source=openai))

Beyond his research, Nasab has been active in advocating for international students. In 2017, he authored an article in *Science* magazine titled "Standing up to fear," discussing the challenges faced by international students in the U.S. amid political changes. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, Nasab has contributed to discussions on professional development, sharing insights on successful job interviews through his Medium blog. ([ali-khaledi1989.medium.com](https://ali-khaledi1989.medium.com/an-introduction-to-a-successful-job-interview-b4925c49d98?utm_source=openai))

His academic contributions are also documented on platforms like Academia.edu and exaly.com, where he has published multiple papers and has a notable h-index, indicating significant citations in his field. ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai), [exaly.com](https://exaly.com/author/5034433/ali-khaledi-nasab?utm_source=openai))

task_3.query_used: Search academic publication databases for research papers or academic credentials
task_3.data:
Dr. Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and AI scientist with a diverse academic and professional background. He earned his Ph.D. in Physics and Astronomy from Ohio University, where he focused on the collective dynamics of excitable tree networks, particularly in sensory neurons with myelinated dendrites. His doctoral research led to several publications, including "Emergent stochastic oscillations and signal detection in tree networks of excitable elements" and "Information processing in tree networks of excitable elements." ([stanford.academia.edu](https://stanford.academia.edu/AliKhalediNasab?swp=tc-au-6993172&utm_source=openai))

After completing his Ph.D., Dr. Khaledi Nasab worked as a postdoctoral researcher at Stanford University's Department of Neurosurgery, collaborating with Peter Tass on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders such as Parkinson's disease. He also served as an adjunct professor of Physics at Ohio University. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

In 2022, he joined Amazon as a research scientist in the Network Capacity Planning organization, focusing on AI and machine learning applications. His interdisciplinary expertise spans nonlinear dynamics, stochastic processes, signal processing, statistics, biophysics, and network sciences. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

Dr. Khaledi Nasab has been recognized for his contributions to the field, receiving the American Physical Society (APS) Division of Biological Physics 2019 Student Travel Award to attend the annual APS meeting in Boston, where he presented his research on sensory neurons. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2019/05/khaledi-nasab-receives-aps-travel-award-to-attend-conference/?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, he has engaged in public discourse, authoring an article titled "Standing up to fear," which reflects on the challenges faced by international students in the U.S. amid political changes. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

For a comprehensive overview of his work and publications, you can visit his personal website. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))
